05042nam a22005655i 9780226384399DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015048965  a9780226384399  a(DE-B1597)568203  a(OCoLC)1233040681  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH366.2b.R5238 2016 4aQH366.2b.R5238 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a576.8/2223  aHL 25652rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50548:118521 aRichards, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDebating Darwin /cMichael Ruse, Robert J. Richards. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b21 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tTIMELINE -- tCHARLES DARWIN: GREAT BRITON -- tCHARLES DARWIN: COSMOPOLITAN THINKER -- tRESPONSE TO RUSE -- tREPLY TO RICHARDS -- tEPILOGUE -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCharles Darwin is easily the most famous scientist of the modern age, and his theory of evolution is constantly referenced in many contexts by scientists and nonscientists alike. And yet, despite how frequently his ideas are evoked, there remains a surprising amount we don’t know about the father of modern evolutionary thinking, his intellectual roots, and the science he produced. Debating Darwin seeks to change that, bringing together two leading Darwin scholars—Robert J. Richards and Michael Ruse—to engage in a spirited and insightful dialogue, offering their interpretations of Darwin and their critiques of each other’s thinking. Examining key disagreements about Darwin that continue to confound even committed Darwinists, Richards and Ruse offer divergent views on the origins and nature of Darwin and his ideas. Ruse argues that Darwin was quintessentially British and that the roots of his thought can be traced back to the eighteenth century, particularly to the Industrial Revolution and thinkers such as Adam Smith and Thomas Robert Malthus. Ruse argues that when these influences are appreciated, we can see how Darwin’s work in biology is an extension of their theories. In contrast, Richards presents Darwin as a more cosmopolitan, self-educated man, influenced as much by French and particularly German thinkers. Above all, argues Richards, it was Alexander von Humboldt who both inspired Darwin and gave him the conceptual tools that he needed to find and formulate his evolutionary hypotheses. Together, the authors show how the reverberations of the contrasting views on Darwin’s influences can be felt in theories about the nature of natural selection, the role of metaphor in science, and the place of God in Darwin’s thought. Revealing how much there still is to investigate and interrogate about Darwin’s ideas, Debating Darwin contributes to our understanding of evolution itself. The book concludes with a jointly authored chapter that brings this debate into the present, focusing on human evolution, consciousness, religion, and morality. This will be powerful, essential reading for anyone seeking a comprehensive understanding of modern-day evolutionary science and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEvolution (Biology) 0aEvolution (Biology). 0aEvolution. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  adarwinian, evolution, evolutionary, genes, genetics, science, scientist, scientific, modern, contemporary, theory, theoretical, biography, biographical, intellectual, thinker, philosophical, industrial revolution, origin, species, religion, religious, faith, belief, controversial, controversy, biology, natural, selection, nature, moral, mankind, naturalist, teleology.1 aRuse, Michael, eauthor.4aut4htt